---
import BaseLayout from "~/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import ThermoacousticAnimation from "~/components/research/ThermoacousticAnimation.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  lang="en"
  title="Animation · Standing-Wave"
  description="Interactive animation of the thermoacoustic effect: standing-wave engines and refrigerators in three regimes (uniform, refrigerator, engine), with synchronized gas-parcel oscillation, P–V trajectory, and T–x trajectory."
>
  <section class="py-8">
    <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-brand-500">
      Research / Animations
    </p>
    <h1 class="mt-2 text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-brand-900">
      Thermoacoustic Mechanism Animation
    </h1>
    <p class="mt-2 text-xl font-light tracking-wide text-brand-600">
      Standing-Wave Type · 駐波型
    </p>
    <div class="mt-3 h-1 w-16 bg-accent-500" aria-hidden="true"></div>
    <p class="mt-6 max-w-3xl text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-700">
      The thermoacoustic effect emerges from the coupling of two phenomena: the
      oscillation of gas parcels in a temperature gradient, and the heat
      exchange between those parcels and the surrounding walls. Following the
      schematic concepts from G. W. Swift's and T. Biwa's thermoacoustics
      textbooks, the animation below switches between three regimes — uniform,
      refrigerator, and engine — and lets you observe damped spirals,
      counter-clockwise closed orbits, and clockwise closed orbits in the phase
      space.
    </p>
  </section>

  <ThermoacousticAnimation />

  <section class="mt-12 max-w-3xl">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-brand-900">How to read this animation</h2>

    <h3 class="mt-6 text-lg font-medium text-brand-800">① Gas parcel inside the stack</h3>
    <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">
      Top wide strip: the resonator with the stack in the middle (the array of
      horizontal lines represents the stack plates). The cyan rectangle is the
      gas parcel under observation, oscillating left and right and changing
      volume (compression / expansion) periodically with the acoustic wave.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-6 text-lg font-medium text-brand-800">② Close-up of the gas parcel</h3>
    <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">
      Top-right inset: a close-up of the parcel and the two adjacent stack
      plates. Red arrows indicate the direction and magnitude of <strong>radial
      heat transfer</strong> between the parcel and the plates (arrow thickness
      ∝ heat flux).
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-6 text-lg font-medium text-brand-800">③ p–ξ / p–V trajectories</h3>
    <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">
      Top-left: two trajectories overlaid, each with its own physical meaning.
    </p>
    <ul class="mt-2 list-disc space-y-1 pl-6 text-gray-700">
      <li>
        <strong style="color:#d97706">Orange <i>p</i>–<i>ξ</i> (pressure–displacement)</strong>:
        loop area × <i>ω</i>/(2π) = <strong>acoustic intensity <i>I</i></strong>
        (⟨<i>p</i>·<i>u</i>⟩, where the parcel oscillates with velocity
        <i>u</i> = d<i>ξ</i>/d<i>t</i>). Corresponds to the bottom-plane
        projection of the 3D orbit.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong style="color:#0e7490">Cyan dashed <i>p</i>–<i>V</i> (pressure–volume)</strong>:
        the classical thermodynamic PV diagram; loop area
        ∮<i>p</i> d<i>V</i> = <strong>work per cycle <i>W</i></strong>. More
        intuitive for readers familiar with heat-engine cycles.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">
      Both close clockwise (engine) ⇒ acoustic power output; counter-clockwise
      (refrigerator) ⇒ acoustic power input pumping heat; degenerate to a line
      (critical / flat) ⇒ no net effect. The two shapes differ slightly because
      <i>ξ</i> and <i>V</i> have different phase relationships for the same
      parcel (in a standing wave, they are not perfectly in phase).
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-6 text-lg font-medium text-brand-800">④ <i>T</i>–<i>x</i> (temperature–position) trajectory</h3>
    <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">
      Bottom-left: the dark-green ellipse is the parcel temperature versus
      position; the orange dashed line is the wall temperature gradient. The
      <strong>position of the ellipse relative to the dashed line</strong>
      determines the radial heat-transfer direction: when the parcel is hotter
      than the wall, heat flows to the wall; when colder, heat flows into the
      parcel. As the parcel oscillates, it picks up heat at one end, carries
      it, and releases it at the other end — the heart of the thermoacoustic
      effect as a heat engine / refrigerator.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700 text-sm">
      Note: this plot conceptually corresponds to the "entropy <i>S</i> vs
      displacement <i>ξ</i> projection ≈ <i>Q</i>" face of the 3D orbit, but
      the vertical axis here is <strong>temperature <i>T</i></strong>, not
      entropy <i>S</i>. For a single parcel under adiabatic conditions
      d<i>T</i> ∝ d<i>S</i>, so the shape is similar; the units differ (<i>T</i>
      carries an extra heat-capacity factor), so the loop area is
      <strong>proportional to</strong> heat flux <i>Q</i> rather than strictly
      equal to it. The ellipse uses a darker shade
      (<span style="color:#15803d">●</span>) than the 3D-projection green
      (<span style="color:#16a34a">●</span>) to flag this "related but not
      identical" relationship.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-10 text-2xl font-semibold text-brand-900">The three regimes and their wall-temperature gradients</h2>
    <table class="mt-4 w-full text-sm">
      <thead class="text-left text-brand-700">
        <tr class="border-b-2 border-brand-200">
          <th class="py-2 pr-4">Mode</th>
          <th class="py-2 pr-4">Wall gradient</th>
          <th class="py-2">Physical meaning</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody class="text-gray-700">
        <tr class="border-b border-brand-100">
          <td class="py-2 pr-4 font-medium">Flat (uniform)</td>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4">None</td>
          <td class="py-2">No wall gradient; neither pump nor engine. The parcel oscillates purely adiabatically.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-brand-100">
          <td class="py-2 pr-4 font-medium">Refrigerator</td>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4">Shallow</td>
          <td class="py-2">Wall gradient smaller than the parcel's adiabatic gradient; external work input pumps heat from cold to hot.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4 font-medium">Engine</td>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4">Steep</td>
          <td class="py-2">Wall gradient steeper than the parcel's adiabatic gradient; heat flows from hot to cold and the parcel outputs acoustic power.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p class="mt-8 flex flex-wrap gap-x-5 gap-y-2 text-sm text-gray-500">
      <a href="/en/research/animations" class="underline hover:text-accent-600">← Back to animation index</a>
      <a href="/en/research/thermoacoustic-effect" class="underline hover:text-accent-600">The Thermoacoustic Effect</a>
    </p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
